  "prompt": "The club has 37 members, 20 of whom are women and 17 of whom are men. The club needs to form a 4 person party-planning committee. How many committees are possible if the committee must have 2 women and 2 men?",
  "response": "Let $C(n, k)$ denote the number of combinations of choosing $k$ items from a set of $n$ items, which is given by the binomial coefficient $\\binom{n}{k} = \\frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}$.\n\nWe need to form a 4-person committee with 2 women and 2 men.\nThe number of women in the club is 20. We need to choose 2 women from the 20 available. This can be done in $C(20, 2)$ ways.\n$C(20, 2) = \\binom{20}{2} = \\frac{20!}{2!(20-2)!} = \\frac{20!}{2!18!} = \\frac{20 \\times 19}{2 \\times 1} = 10 \\times 19 = 190$\n\nThe number of men in the club is 17. We need to choose 2 men from the 17 available. This can be done in $C(17, 2)$ ways.\n$C(17, 2) = \\binom{17}{2} = \\frac{17!}{2!(17-2)!} = \\frac{17!}{2!15!} = \\frac{17 \\times 16}{2 \\times 1} = 17 \\times 8 = 136$\n\nSince we need to choose 2 women and 2 men, we multiply the number of ways to choose the women by the number of ways to choose the men.\nTotal number of committees possible = $C(20, 2) \\times C(17, 2) = 190 \\times 136$\n$190 \\times 136 = (200 - 10) \\times 136 = 200 \\times 136 - 10 \\times 136 = 27200 - 1360 = 25840$\n\nTherefore, the number of possible committees with 2 women and 2 men is 25840.\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{25840}$",
